{"title_page": "18 Scorpii", "text_new": "{{Starbox begin\n| name = 18 Scorpii\n}}\n{{Starbox image\n | image = \n     <div style=\"position: relative\">[[File:Scorpius IAU.svg|250px|alt=Diagram showing star positions and boundaries of the Scorpius constellation and its surroundings]]\n     <div style=\"position: absolute; left: 63.2%; top: 17.4%;\">[[File:Cercle rouge 100%.svg|12px]]</div>\n     </div>\n | caption=Location of 18 Scorpii (circled)\n}}\n{{Starbox observe\n| epoch = [[J2000.0]]\n| constell = [[Scorpius]]\n| ra = {{RA|16|15|37.26946}}<ref name=aaa474_2_653/>\n| dec = {{DEC|\u201308|22|09.9870}}<ref name=aaa474_2_653/>\n| appmag_v = 5.503<ref name=aaa418_989/>\n}}\n{{Starbox character\n| class = G2&nbsp;Va\n| b-v = +0.64<ref name=SIMBAD/>\n| u-b = +0.18<ref name=SIMBAD/>\n| variable = Sun-like<ref name=aj138_1_312/>\n}}\n{{Starbox astrometry\n| radial_v = +11.6<ref name=aaa418_989/>\n| parallax = 71.94\n| p_error = 0.37\n| parallax_footnote = <ref name=aaa474_2_653/>\n| prop_mo_ra = 230.77<ref name=aaa474_2_653/>\n| prop_mo_dec = -495.53<ref name=aaa474_2_653/>\n| absmag_v = 4.77<ref name=aaa418_989/>\n}}\n{{Starbox detail\n| mass = {{nowrap|1.02 \u00b1 0.03}}<ref name=aaa526_L4/>\n| radius = {{nowrap|1.010 \u00b1 0.009}}<ref name=aaa526_L4/>\n| luminosity = {{nowrap|1.058 \u00b1 0.028}}<ref name=apj746_1_101/>\n| temperature = {{nowrap|5,433 \u00b1 69}}<ref name=apj746_1_101/>\n| gravity = 4.45<ref name=aaa487_1_373/>\n| metal_fe = 0.04<ref name=aaa487_1_373/>\n| age_gyr = {{Val|2.9|0.5}}<ref>[https://exoplanets.nasa.gov/news/122/identification-of-oldest-solar-twin-may-help-locate-rocky-exoplanets/ NASA, Identification of oldest solar twin may help locate rocky exoplanets]</ref>\n| rotation = {{nowrap|22.7 \u00b1 0.5}}<ref name=baas42_333/>\n}}\n{{ Starbox catalog\n| names = [[Star catalogue#BD/CD/CPD|BD]]-07&nbsp;4242, [[Gliese Catalogue of Nearby Stars|Gl]]&nbsp;616, [[Henry Draper Catalogue|HD]]&nbsp;146233, [[Hipparcos catalogue|HIP]]&nbsp;79672, [[Star catalogue#BS, BSC, HR|HR]]&nbsp;6060, [[Star catalogue#SAO|SAO]]&nbsp;141066, GC&nbsp;21864, CCDM&nbsp;16156-0822.<ref name=SIMBAD/>\n}}\n{{Starbox reference\n| Simbad = 18+Sco\n| NSTED = 18+Sco\n}}\n{{Starbox end}}\n\n'''18 Scorpii''' is a solitary [[star]] located at a distance of some {{Convert|45.3|ly|pc|abbr=off|lk=on}} from [[Earth]] at the northern edge of the [[Scorpius|Scorpius constellation]]. It has an [[apparent visual magnitude]] of 5.5,<ref name=aaa418_989/> which is [[Bortle Dark-Sky Scale|bright enough]] to be seen with the naked eye outside of urban areas.\n\n18 Scorpii has some physical properties in common with the [[Sun]], a [[G-type star]]. Cayrel de Strobel (1996) included it in her review of the stars most similar to the Sun,<ref name=aar7_3_243/> and Porto de Mello & da Silva (1997) identified it as a younger [[solar twin]].<ref>[http://www.eso.org/public/images/eso1337a/ ESO, The life cycle of a Sun-like star (annotated), from [[European Southern Observatory]], 28 August 2013]</ref><ref name=apj482_2_L89/> Some scientists therefore believe the prospects for [[life]] in its vicinity are good. However, no planet has yet been discovered orbiting this star.\n\n== Characteristics ==\n[[File:18 scorpii-map.png|left|240px|thumb|18 scorpii is on the northern boundary of the constellation. Its high [[proper motion]] positions it in Ophiuchus before 1700.]]\n18 Scorpii is a [[main sequence]] star of [[stellar classification|spectral and luminosity type]] G2&nbsp;Va,<ref name=apj482_2_L89/> with the luminosity class of 'V' indicating it is generating energy through the [[nuclear fusion]] of hydrogen in its core region. Sousa ''et al.'' (2008) found its [[metallicity]] to be about 1.1 times that of the Sun, which means the abundance of elements other than hydrogen or helium is 10% greater.<ref name=aaa487_1_373/><ref name=metal/> The radius of this star, as measured using [[Astronomical interferometer|interferometry]] by Bazot ''et al.'' (2011), is 101% the [[Solar radius|radius of the Sun]]. When combined with the results of [[asteroseismology]] measurements, this allows the mass of the star to be estimated as 102% of the [[Solar mass|Sun's mass]].<ref name=aaa526_L4/> This star is radiating 106% of the Sun's luminosity from its [[stellar atmosphere|outer atmosphere]] at an [[effective temperature]] of 5,433&nbsp;K.<ref name=apj746_1_101/> It is this heat that gives the star the yellow-hued glow of a [[G-type star]].<ref name=csiro/>\n\nAccording to Lockwood (2002), it has a temporal [[Photometry (astronomy)|photometric]] behavior very similar to the Sun.<ref name=baas34_651/> Its brightness variation over its entire activity cycle is 0.09%, about the same as the Sun's brightness variations during recent solar cycles.<ref name=aj133_5_2206/> Using the technique of [[Zeeman-Doppler imaging]], Petit et al. (2008) have detected its surface magnetic field, showing that its intensity and geometry are very similar to the large-scale solar magnetic field.<ref name=mnras388_1_80/> The estimated period for the activity cycle of 18 Scorpii is about seven years,<ref name=aj138_1_312/> which is significantly shorter than the Sun's, and its overall chromospheric activity level is noticeably higher.<ref name=aj133_5_2206/><ref name=apj545_2_L43/> Like the Sun, it has a hot [[stellar corona|corona]] with a temperature in the range of 1.5\u20132&nbsp;MK and an [[X-ray astronomy|X-ray]] luminosity of {{nowrap|8 \u00b1 1.5 ergs s<sup>\u22121</sup>}}.<ref name=baas42_333/>\n\nThough 18 Scorpii is only slightly more metal-rich overall than the Sun, its lithium abundance is about three times as high; for this reason, Mel\u00e9ndez & Ram\u00edrez (2007) have suggested that 18 Scorpii be called a \"quasi solar twin\", reserving the term [[solar twin]] for stars (such as [[Hipparcos catalogue|HIP]] [[HIP 56948|56948]]) that match the Sun, within the observational errors, for all parameters.<ref name=apj669_2_L89/>\n\n18 Scorpii is a young star at 2.9 Gyr (2.9 Billion years old). 18 Scorpii has not yet entered its stable burning stage. The Sun at 4.7 Gyr is at its most stable stage. Due to 18 Scorpii age, it is at the edge of range for a solar twin, and is more of a Solar analog.<ref>{{Cite journal |arxiv = astro-ph/0508004|last1 = King|first1 = Jeremy R|title = Keck/HIRES Spectroscopy of Four Candidate Solar Twins|journal = The Astronomical Journal|volume = 130|issue = 5|pages = 2318\u20132325|last2 = Boesgaard|first2 = Ann M|last3 = Schuler|first3 = Simon C|year = 2005|doi = 10.1086/452640|bibcode = 2005AJ....130.2318K}}</ref>\n\n18 Scorpii was identified in September 2003 by astrobiologist [[Margaret Turnbull]] from the [[University of Arizona]] in [[Tucson]] as one of the most promising nearby candidates for hosting life, based on her analysis of the [[HabCat]] list of stars. This is a solitary star and, as of 2005, radial velocity measurements have not yet revealed the presence of planets orbiting it.<ref name=\"mea2005\"/> Nor does this star display the level of [[infrared excess|excess infrared emission]] that would otherwise suggest the presence of unconsolidated circumstellar matter, such as a [[debris disk]].<ref name=apj705_1_89/>\n\n18 Scorpii was thought to be 5.0 billion years old in the past, new measurements in 2013 found 18 Scorpii to be younger at 2.9 billion years old.<ref>[https://exoplanets.nasa.gov/news/122/identification-of-oldest-solar-twin-may-help-locate-rocky-exoplanets/ NASA NEWS, Identification of oldest solar twin may help locate rocky exoplanets,  August 29, 2013]</ref>\n\n[[File:The_life_cycle_of_a_Sun-like_star_(annotated).jpg|thumb|left|300px|The age of 18 Scorpii, shown relative to the Sun, the older solar twin [[HD 197027]], here annotated as HIP 102152 and the formation of the [[Milky Way]]]]\n{{clearleft}}\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|refs=\n\n<ref name=aaa474_2_653>{{cite journal | last1=van Leeuwen | first1=F. | title=Validation of the new Hipparcos reduction | journal=Astronomy and Astrophysics | volume=474 | issue=2 | pages=653\u2013664 | bibcode=2007A&A...474..653V | doi=10.1051/0004-6361:20078357 |arxiv = 0708.1752 |year=2007}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=aaa418_989>{{cite journal | title=The Geneva-Copenhagen survey of the Solar neighbourhood. Ages, metallicities, and kinematic properties of \u02dc14 000 F and G dwarfs | display-authors=1 | last1=Nordstr\u00f6m | first1=B. | last2=Mayor | first2=M. | last3=Andersen | first3=J. | last4=Holmberg | first4=J. | last5=Pont | first5=F. | last6=J\u00f8rgensen | first6=B. R. | last7=Olsen | first7=E. H. | last8=Udry | first8=S. | last9=Mowlavi | first9=N. | journal=Astronomy and Astrophysics | volume=418 | issue=3 | pages=989\u20131019    | doi=10.1051/0004-6361:20035959 | bibcode=2004A&A...418..989N |arxiv = astro-ph/0405198  |year=2004}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=SIMBAD>{{citation | title=18 Sco -- Variable Star | work=SIMBAD | publisher=Centre de Donn\u00e9es astronomiques de Strasbourg | url=http://simbad.u-strasbg.fr/simbad/sim-id?Ident=18+Sco | accessdate=2011-10-13 }} The ubv information is per ''Compilation of Eggen's UBV data, transformed to UBV'' (unpublished) 1986. See the Measurements section.</ref>\n\n<ref name=aj138_1_312>{{cite journal | display-authors=1 | last1=Hall | first1=Jeffrey C. | last2=Henry | first2=Gregory W. | last3=Lockwood | first3=G. Wesley | last4=Skiff | first4=Brian A. | last5=Saar | first5=Steven H. | title=The Activity and Variability of the Sun and Sun-Like Stars. II. Contemporaneous Photometry and Spectroscopy of Bright Solar Analogs | journal=The Astronomical Journal | volume=138 | issue=1 | pages=312\u2013322   | doi=10.1088/0004-6256/138/1/312 | bibcode=2009AJ....138..312H  |date=July 2009| citeseerx=10.1.1.216.9004 }}</ref>\n\n<ref name=aaa526_L4>{{cite journal | display-authors=1 | last1=Bazot | first1=M. | last2=Ireland | first2=M. J. | last3=Huber | first3=D. | last4=Bedding | first4=T. R. | last5=Broomhall | first5=A.-M. | last6=Campante | first6=T. L. | last7=Carfantan | first7=H. | last8=Chaplin | first8=W. J. | last9=Elsworth | first9=Y. | title=The radius and mass of the close solar twin 18 Scorpii derived from asteroseismology and interferometry | journal=Astronomy and Astrophysics | volume=526   | issue=526 | pages=L4 | doi=10.1051/0004-6361/201015679 | bibcode=2011A&A...526L...4B |arxiv = 1209.0217  |date=February 2011}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=aaa487_1_373>{{cite journal | display-authors=1 | last1=Sousa | first1=S. G. | last2=Santos | first2=N. C. | last3=Mayor | first3=M. | last4=Udry | first4=S. | last5=Casagrande | first5=L. | last6=Israelian | first6=G. | last7=Pepe | first7=F. | last8=Queloz | first8=D. | last9=Monteiro | first9=M. J. P. F. G. | title=Spectroscopic parameters for 451 stars in the HARPS GTO planet search program. Stellar [Fe/H] and the frequency of exo-Neptunes | journal=Astronomy and Astrophysics | volume=487 | issue=1 | pages=373\u2013381   | doi=10.1051/0004-6361:200809698 | bibcode=2008A&A...487..373S | arxiv=0805.4826  |date=August 2008 }}</ref>\n\n<ref name=aar7_3_243>{{cite journal | last1=Cayrel de Strobel | first1=G. | year=1996 | title=Stars Resembling the Sun | journal=[[The Astronomy and Astrophysics Review]] | volume=7 | issue=3 | pages=243\u2013288 | doi=10.1007/s001590050006|bibcode=1996A&ARv...7..243C }}</ref>\n\n<ref name=apj482_2_L89>{{cite journal | last1=Porto de Mello | first1=G. F. | last2=da Silva | first2=L. | year=1997 | title=HR 6060: The Closest Ever Solar Twin? | journal=[[The Astrophysical Journal]] | volume=482 | issue=2 | pages=L89\u2013L92 | doi=10.1086/310693 | bibcode=1997ApJ...482L..89P}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=metal>A metallicity of [Fe/H] = 1.04 dex indicates that the star has 10<sup>0.04</sup> = 1.096, or 110% of the abundance of elements heavier than helium, compared to the Sun.</ref>\n\n<ref name=apj669_2_L89>{{cite journal | last1=Mel\u00e9ndez | first1=J. | last2=Ram\u00edrez | first2=I. | year=2007 | title=HIP 56948: A Solar Twin wit