Umbra, from [[Mount Hasan]] southeast of [[\u0130ncesu, Aksaray]], Turkey\n* [http://www.krysstal.com/ec2006.html The 2006 Eclipse in Turkey]\n* [http://www.izmiran.ru/info/personalia/molodensky/Eclips06.html Russian scientist observed eclipse]\n* [https://archive.is/20060405115220/http://solar-eclipse.uoa.gr/english/ University of Athens \u2013 Solar Eclipse 29/3/2006, Solar Party]\n* [http://www.eclipse2006.boun.edu.tr/eclipse_2006eng.html Solar Total Eclipse of 2006 March 29]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20061001175754/http://www.tug.tubitak.gov.tr/tutulma/english/main.html Tubitak.gov.tr], 29 March 2006 Total Solar Eclipse, [[Scientific and Technological Research Council of Turkey]] (T\u00dcB\u0130TAK)\n* [https://plus.google.com/u/0/photos/114683585900298102409/albums/5860884632549337137 Solar Eclipse over Kemer, Turkey 060329]\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category-inline}}\n{{Solar eclipses}}\n\n[[Category:Total solar eclipses|2006 03 29]]\n[[Category:2006 in science]]\n[[Category:21st-century solar eclipses|2006 03 29]]\n[[Category:March 2006 events]]\n[[Category:2006 in Ghana]]\n[[Category:2006 in Togo]]\n[[Category:2006 in Benin]]\n[[Category:2006 in Nigeria]]\n[[Category:2006 in Niger]]\n[[Category:2006 in Chad]]\n[[Category:2006 in Libya]]\n[[Category:2006 in Egypt]]\n[[Category:2006 in Turkey]]\n[[Category:2006 in Georgia (country)]]\n[[Category:2006 in Russia]]\n[[Category:2006 in Kazakhstan]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox solar eclipse|2006Mar29}}\nA total [[solar eclipse]] occurred on March 28\u201329, 2006. A solar eclipse occurs when the [[Moon]] passes between [[Earth]] and the [[Sun]], thereby totally or partly obscuring the image of the Sun for a viewer on Earth. A total solar eclipse occurs when the Moon's [[apparent diameter]] is larger than the Sun's, blocking all direct sunlight, turning day into darkness. Totality occurs in a narrow path across Earth's surface, with the partial solar eclipse visible over a surrounding region thousands of kilometres wide. It was visible from a narrow corridor which traversed half the [[Earth]]. The [[magnitude of eclipse|magnitude]], that is, the ratio between the apparent sizes of the Moon and that of the Sun, was 1.052, and it was part of Saros 139.\n\n== Visibility ==\n[[File:Solar eclipse animate (2006-Mar-29).gif|thumb|left|Animated path]]\nThe path of totality of the [[Moon]]'s shadow began at sunrise in [[Brazil]] and extended across the [[Atlantic Ocean|Atlantic]] to [[Africa]], traveling across [[Ghana]], the southeastern tip of [[Ivory Coast]], [[Togo]], [[Benin]], [[Nigeria]], [[Niger]], [[Chad]], [[Libya]], and a small corner of northwest [[Egypt]], from there across the [[Mediterranean Sea]] to [[Greece]] ([[Kastell\u00f3rizo]]) and [[Turkey]], then across the [[Black Sea]] via [[Georgia (country)|Georgia]], [[Russia]], and [[Kazakhstan]] to Western [[Mongolia]], where it ended at sunset. A [[Solar eclipse|partial eclipse]] was seen from the much broader path of the [[Moon]]'s [[penumbra]], including the northern two-thirds of [[Africa]], the whole of [[Europe]], and [[Central Asia]].\n\n==Observations==\nPeople around the world gathered in areas where the eclipse was visible to view the event. The [[Manchester Astronomical Society]], the [[Malaysian Space Agency]], the [[Astronomical Society of the Pacific]], as well as dozens of tour groups met at the Apollo temple and the theater in [[Side, Turkey|Side]], [[Turkey]]. The San Francisco [[Exploratorium]] featured a live webcast from the site, where thousands of observers were seated in the ancient, Roman-style theater.<ref>[http://www.exploratorium.edu/eclipse/2006/index.html Total Solar Eclipse: Live from Turkey in 2006<!--Bot-generated title-->]</ref>\n\nAlmost all actively visited areas in the path of totality had perfect weather. Many observers reported an unusually beautiful eclipse, with many or all effects visible, and a very nice [[corona]], despite the proximity to the [[solar minimum]]. The partial phase of the eclipse was also visible from the [[International Space Station]], where the astronauts on board took spectacular pictures of the moon's shadow on [[Earth]]'s surface. It initially appeared as though an orbit correction set for the middle of March would bring the ISS into the path of totality, but this correction was postponed.\n\n== Gallery==\n<center>\n<gallery>\nImage:Totality_libya_2006.jpg|[[Sahara]], Libya, 12:11 local time (10:11 UTC)\nImage:Eclipse Sol 290306 Valencia.jpg|[[Valencia, Spain]], 12:16 local time (10:16 UTC)\nImage:Diamondring-eclipse-March03-29-2006.jpg|[[Side, Turkey]], 13:55 local time (10:55 UTC)\nImage:Eclipse fromISS 2006-03-29.jpg|[[International Space Station]] over [[Turkey]] and [[Cyprus]], 13:57 local time (10:57 UTC)\nImage:Eclipse 29032006.jpg|[[Berkhamsted, England]], 12:01 local time (11:01 UTC)\nImage:Eclipsenovosib.jpg|[[Novosibirsk, Russia]], 18:42 local time (11:42 UTC)\nImage:eclipse_krasnoyarsk_29_03_2006.jpg|[[Krasnoyarsk, Russia]], 20:21 local time (12:11 UTC)\nImage:zatm_lagan.jpg|[[Kalmykia]], Russia, 16:22 local time (12:22 UTC)\nImage:20060329sequence.jpg|[[Degania A]], Israel: The Solar Eclipse\nFile:Animation eclipse.gif \n</gallery>\n</center>\n\n==Satellite failure==\n{{Main|Optus fleet of satellites#Failures}}\nThe satellite responsible for [[SKY Network Television]], a New Zealand pay TV company, failed the day after this eclipse at around 1900 local time. While SKY didn't directly attribute the failure to the eclipse, they said in a media release that it took longer to resolve the issue because of it, but this claim was refuted by astronomers.<!--<ref>Stuff.co.nz, [http://www.stuff.co.nz/stuff/0,2106,3622764a10,00.html Astronomer refutes Sky TV eclipse explanation] 31 March 2006.</ref>--> The main reason for the failure was because of an aging and increasingly faulty satellite.<ref>Press release by Sky TV. [http://www.sky.co.nz/index.cfm?pageid=469&script=newsrelease&dsp=nr&newsid=197&nrcontent=0 Solar eclipse interferes with satellite restoration] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20050210040426/http://sky.co.nz/index.cfm?pageid=469 |date=2005-02-10 }} Friday, 31 March 2006.</ref>\n\n==Related eclipses==\n=== Eclipses of 2006 ===\n* [[March 2006 lunar eclipse|A penumbral lunar eclipse on March 14]].\n* A total solar eclipse on March 29.\n* [[September 2006 lunar eclipse|A partial lunar eclipse on September 7]].\n* [[Solar eclipse of September 22, 2006|An annular solar eclipse on September 22]].\n\nThis solar eclipse was preceded by the [[March 2006 lunar eclipse|penumbral lunar eclipse on March 14, 2006]].\n\n=== Solar eclipses 2004\u20132007 ===\n{{Solar eclipse set 2004\u20132007}}\n\n=== Saros 139 ===\n{{Solar Saros series 139}}\n\n===Inex series===\n{{Inex eclipse set info}}\n{| class=\"wikitable collapsible collapsed\"\n!colspan=3| Inex series members between 1901 and 2100:\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|[[File:SE1919May29T.png|150px]]<br />[[solar eclipse of May 29, 1919|May 29, 1919]]<br />(Saros 136)\n|[[File:SE1948May09A.png|150px]]<br />[[solar eclipse of May 9, 1948|May 9, 1948]]<br />(Saros 137)\n|[[File:SE1977Apr18A.png|150px]]<br />[[solar eclipse of April 18, 1977|April 18, 1977]]<br />(Saros 138)\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|[[File:SE2006Mar29T.png|150px]]<br />March 29, 2006<br />(Saros 139)\n|[[File:SE2035Mar09A.png|150px]]<br />[[solar eclipse of March 9, 2035|March 9, 2035]]<br />(Saros 140)\n|[[File:SE2064Feb17A.png|150px]]<br />[[solar eclipse of February 17, 2064|February 17, 2064]]<br />(Saros 141)\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|[[File:SE2093Jan27T.png|150px]]<br />[[solar eclipse of January 27, 2093|January 27, 2093]]<br />(Saros 142)\n|\n|}\n\n=== Metonic series===\n{{Solar Metonic series 2002 June 10}}\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==References==\n* [[Fred Espenak]] and Jay Anderson. \"''[https://web.archive.org/web/20060409085209/http://sunearth.gsfc.nasa.gov/eclipse/SEpubs/TP212762a.pdf Total Solar E